Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_1582
Response Text: Austin’s creative community is full of organizations doing important work, but a lot of them are under-supported or overlooked. ACME can better support these groups by making sure they are actually being listened to. That means going beyond the usual circles and reaching out directly to a wider range of arts organizations, especially the ones that don’t already have a seat at the table.

Right now, a lot of opportunities like grants, events, or resources are hard to find unless you already know someone in the loop. There needs to be more intentional outreach and communication so that smaller or newer organizations aren’t left out just because they don’t have the same access.

There also needs to be more transparency around funding. The city offers grants, but the process can feel really confusing if you don’t have a full development team or someone who knows the system inside and out. It would make a huge difference if the grant process was more open and easier to understand. Clearer timelines, more educational support, and real explanations about how decisions are made and why. Demystifying that process would help level the playing field.

And beyond just money, visibility matters. ACME has a platform and can help by amplifying the work of local creatives. Not just the big names, but the grassroots orgs doing powerful, community-driven work.

We also need regular spaces for artists to be heard. Town halls, surveys, feedback sessions that are standard, not occasional. If ACME is serious about equity and support, it has to build those conversations into the way it operates.

